 views and illuminate the cultural impact of globalization on different societies around the world: Africa, Asia, Europe, and the Americas. These societies face complex questions regarding people's histories, identities, and cultures that embody the ambivalence, contradictions, and anxieties generated by the process of globalization. The contributors provide a compelling conclusion for a rethinking and reconfiguration of cultures and intercultural relations in today's global world in which dichotomized representations coexist with a discourse of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCultural policy. 0aGlobalization. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aSocial sciences. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aApter, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehdad, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirlik, Arif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEze, Emmanuel Chukwudi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlissant, Edouard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Akhil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanmohamed, Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJulien, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMignolo, Walter D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMudimbe-Boyi, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPratt, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaussy, Haun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchipper, Mineke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu